@CrunkComputing Messages are not just passing SPF they are DKIM signed. Legit from PayPal, but bad actors have accounts. Seeing more of this activity today.

There appears to be a large uptick in emails originating legitimately from @Paypal asking people to pay invoices for something that was never bought. This is a major problem as emails are bypassing spam filters as they are legitimately being sent by PayPal email servers.

@AskPayPal @KeldonAlleyne @sur04sep This reactive approach you’re taking to the issue is quite frankly unacceptable and is raising great concern over the privacy and safety of your customers. How much feedback from your customers do you need to fix the internal problem? Do better.

@KeldonAlleyne @sur04sep @AskPayPal @PayPal That's a scam. The "Invoices" are being generated FROM a bad actor's @PayPal so they appear legitimate to the recipient. These emails are passing SPF/DKIM auth checks. It's a major problem and PayPal needs to do something about it.
